post_text:
This is Dr. Rabey with a reminder, as we prepare to return to school beginning tomorrow, Wednesday, September 9th for our families with last names beginning with A-L and then on Thursday, September 10th for our families with last names beginning with M-Z.

Before your children leave the house, please confirm that they do not have a temperature, symptoms consistent with COVID-19, a positive COVID-19 test result within the last 14 days, have been in close contact with anyone who has been infected with COVID-19 or have traveled to a state that is identified on the NYS Travel Advisory list.

If you are unable to complete a full screening at home, please contact your school nurse, so that arrangements can be made at school. Please note: all students will have their temperature taken upon arrival at school.

Our goal is to protect the health and safety of our entire Depew Family and to ensure that we can continue to deliver face to face instruction for as long as possible. Collectively, as a School-Community, we can make this happen.

Thank you!

post_text:
The first day of attendance for students in the hybrid model will be September 9th.
There will be two weeks of a “soft opening” 9/9 – 9/18.
Students in the hybrid model with last names A-L will attend school on 9/9, 9/11, 9/15 and 9/17.
Students in the hybrid model with last names M-Z will attend school on 9/10, 9/14, 9/16 and 9/18.
During this “soft opening” time, our staff and students will focus on safety protocols and procedures, building relationships, establishing flows of communication and instruction, technology access and training, and a host of other activities as we all get re-acclimated with school.
The first day of academic instruction for both our hybrid and remote learners will be September 21st.

post_text:
As a new school year approaches that is different from any other, we want to hear from you again, this time focusing on the social and emotional components that need to be taken into consideration before we start our new educational journey.

With that in mind, we are asking you to join us in a new ThoughtExchange, which can be found on our website and in your email. The question is: “As we approach September, what excites you and what makes you nervous about returning to school?”

Please share as many thoughts as possible, and we will use your responses to inform our planning and professional development to best support our faculty and staff. Furthermore, your feedback will have a direct influence on the programming for our students during our Soft Reopening Days beginning on Wednesday, September 9th.

The ThoughtExchange will be open until Monday, August 31st at 5:00pm, as we will be holding our four Superintendent Conference Days for Professional Development beginning on September 1st

Thank you!

https://my.thoughtexchange.com/648381980

post_text:
Congratulations are in order to coach Kevin Miller, Lancaster, Iroquois, and Depew's Girls Hockey coach and Depew's Jersey Phillips for receiving awards last week during the virtual Hasek's Heroes Western New York Hockey Awards.

The Girls Federation Coach of the Year award went to Coach Miller who led the Girls team to a regular-season division title and a berth in post-season finals. Rochester native, former Sabre, and 12-year NHL player Brian Gionta presented coach with the honor.

Also, the Girls Federation Offensive Player of the Year went to Jersey Phillips. Buffalo-born palyer with a 19-year NHL career, Todd Marchant presented Jersey with her award. Jersey scored 22 goals and accumulated 40 points this past winter.

The ceremony was named after Hockey Hall of Famer and former Sabre goaltender Dominic Hasek and was MC'd by Sabres MSG host Brian Duff. The entire virtual award presentation can be seen here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xGOudp-O0GI

Congrats Coach and Jersey!
text:
Congratulations are in order to coach Kevin Miller, Lancaster, Iroquois, and Depew's Girls Hockey coach and Depew's Jersey Phillips for receiving awards last week during the virtual Hasek's Heroes Western New York Hockey Awards.

The Girls Federation Coach of the Year award went to Coach Miller who led the Girls team to a regular-season division title and a berth in post-season finals. Rochester native, former Sabre, and 12-year NHL player Brian Gionta presented coach with the honor.

Also, the Girls Federation Offensive Player of the Year went to Jersey Phillips. Buffalo-born palyer with a 19-year NHL career, Todd Marchant presented Jersey with her award. Jersey scored 22 goals and accumulated 40 points this past winter.

The ceremony was named after Hockey Hall of Famer and former Sabre goaltender Dominic Hasek and was MC'd by Sabres MSG host Brian Duff. The entire virtual award presentation can be seen here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xGOudp-O0GI

Congrats Coach and Jersey!

post_text: Feeding the children of Depew during the COVID-19 school closure was a huge success and many lives were positively impacted by this program including the workers, volunteers, teachers and parents. A total of 94,240 hot and cold meals were served from Cayuga Heights and by bus at remote sites and home delivery from March 17 to June 26. We are so proud of the services were able to provide for our children and the community. Thank you to all of our caring staff who made this possible.

post_text: The Depew Union Free School District 2020-21 budget passed with a 1264 (yes) to 997 (no) vote. The purchase of one 48-passenger bus with Wi-Fi from the District Vehicle & Equipment Reserve also passed 1578-675. Thank you for your support! Amy Doody and Nicholas LaMarca were elected to the Board of Education. Their three-year terms start July 1.

Depew High School Academy of Finance
May 22 at 1:49 AM ·

2 of our Seniors won BIG scholarships recently!

Justin Cwiklinski won the Scalp & Blade scholarship worth $10,000
&
Jack Lepczyk won the James Metz Memorial Scholarship worth $5,000

The Scalp & Blade Scholarship is highly competitive. Candidates must have a high standard of scholarship as demonstrated by high school grades, standardized test scores and rank in class. Each candidate must have excellent personal characteristics, habits, diligence, be personable and possess outstanding leadership qualities both inside and outside school activities. Congratulations Justin! The James Metz Memorial Scholarship is awarded to one graduating senior from Lancaster, Depew or St. Mary’s High School. Eligible applicants must have participated in both music and athletics in all four years of high school. Congratulations Jack!! #befutureready

post_text:
May 15, 2020 update from Dr. Rabey:

Friday, May 22 will become a day of remote learning. Directives from the state say students and staff will be required to learn and work on this previously scheduled break. On Thursday, May 21, the meal program will distribute meals for Friday, May 22 and Monday, May 25 (Memorial Day).

Monday, May 25 will remain as a Holiday for Memorial Day for both staff and students.

Thursday, June 11 will be the last day of school for all students. Plans will be communicated about collecting and returning personal belongings from school and returning school property.
Thursday, June 18 will be the last day for teachers.
Friday, June 26 will be the last day of meal distributions and essential workforce child care.

Please continue to check the district website for updates.
Stay Safe.

post_text: Aircraft Owners and Pilots Association, an international not-for-profit organization dedicated to general aviation, featured student pilot Olivia Thornton from Depew. Olivia is a senior from Depew High School and is enrolled in Erie 1 BOCES’ Aviation program at the Harkness Career and Technical Center. According to her feature, her high school experience expanded her knowledge base and deepened her passion to pursue being a pilot. In the fall, she will attend Bowling Green State University with plans to become a commercial pilot. See Olivia’s full Instagram feature. https://www.instagram.com/p/CAGfQTCB6Qo/?igshid=jgot2i8whsll

The CHE Running Club athletes participate in the Independent Health Kids Fun Run at Delaware Park every June. Unfortunately, this event cannot take place "LIVE" this year due to COVID-19. However, Independent Health is rolling out a "VIRTUAL" version of this race!

Register at https://www.kidsrunbuffalo.com/virtual-race-details and select "Wildcats on the Move" as your team.

Instead of going to Delaware Park to run, participate right in your own neighborhood. Coaches Fatta and Oldin would love to have school-wide participation from students and their families.

Don't forget to take a post-race selfie and send it to coldin@depewschools.org!

Today, Governor Cuomo has announced that schools will remain closed for the remainder of the 2019-2020 academic year. However, our remote learning will continue for the remainder of the school year. Students are expected to remain engaged with their teachers and their assigned academic work. Furthermore, the District will continue its established meal distribution plan and the emergency child care program for the essential work force. Please continue to check the District website for updates.
Stay Safe and Take Care,
Dr. Jeffrey Rabey, Superintendent

Parents of students in grades 6-12: As Depew UFSD continues with the mandated COVID-19 school closures, we have modified our grading procedures to provide feedback rather than numeric grades. To monitor this feedback and view your student’s assignments you must now log in to Schoology, the District’s learning management system. The Power School parent portal will no longer provide this information.

If you are unable to log into Schoology or need assistance, please contact your building administrator or Mr. D'Amato at 686-5125 jdamato@depewschool.org.

The login information will be sent to you either by email or US mail. Instructions on how to access and navigate within Schoology are available on our district website, www.depewschools.org/COVID-19.

post_text: We are featuring our middle school staff! Next up is Mrs. Tierney - our speech language pathologist. She and her husband are empty nesters, but they have a busy family life and love their winter ski trips. She said she always knew she wanted a profession that allowed her to help others. "My dad lost part of his hearing when I was young, so I witnessed him struggling to keep up with conversations, especially around the dinner table or at family gatherings, where everyone was trying to talk at once. I didn't realize until I was older how difficult that was for him. Communication is what brings people together, so I was compelled to help others find their voice."

The Depew Union Free School District is partnering with the YMCA Buffalo Niagara to provide childcare to the Depew School-Community residents, who are Health Care Professionals and First Responders at no cost to these families.

The emergency childcare will be provided Monday thru Friday from 7:00 a.m. to 6:00 p.m. at the Cayuga Heights Elementary School and begin Monday, March 23rd.

More information, who to contact and registration forms can be found here: http://www.depewschools.org/o/district/page/coronavirus-resources

More information, who to contact and registration forms can be found here: http://www.depewschools.org/o/district/page/coronavirus-resources

Like Kenny Chesney once said in a song,"Don't Blink" because life is gone before you realize it."

post_text: Four DHS students headed to the DECA State Career Conference & Competition with advisor Ms. Jessica Leary on February 26-28 in Rochester. Chris Burgio placed in the top 10 in the state, competing in the Quick Serve Restaurant Management event. Jordan Kanick also placed in the top 10 in the state, competing in the Principles of Business Management event. Sarah Rolling & Justin Cwiklinski wrote a manual and presented a start-up business plan for their business idea of Animal Avenue which would provide animal care for all types of animals. Sarah was inducted into the National DECA Honor Society and Ms. Leary received a 10-year Service Award. Congratulations!

post_text: First graders in Miss Tedesco's class have been showing off their reading strategies they have been practicing during reader's workshop. These readers have been reading like a STAR in our very own "recording studio" using the application, Seesaw. Students have been scooping up words, changing their voices to sound like the characters, using sound effects, and reading loud and clear to provide kindergarten students with their very own audio books! Our first grade class is full of STAR examples of fluent readers! We are so excited to keep sharing our love of reading with others! Pictured is Star Harper Coyle with Miss Tedesco.

The class has discussions based upon what they've learned.

post_text: On Sunday, March 8 the students in Mrs. Adrienne Marks (middle school) and Mrs. Tracy Malush's (high school) classes performed in the annual SABAH ice show at KeyBank Center. The students were awarded medals to celebrate their performance. The SABAH program will continue into the spring as an adaptive sports program on the turf.

We are featuring our staff. Next up are Mrs. Malone, Mrs. Schreiber and Ms. Tedesco in the Special Education Office!

Ms. Tedesco is a Depew alumna who has worked in the district for three years. She has two dogs at home, Brighton and Fae. She recently binge watched Doc Martin on Netflix and is looking forward to watching The Crown!

Michael Robinson averaged 199 pins for the Wildcats. Devin Bartula and Michael Nikonowicz also contributed to the sectional title. Congratulations!

This past weekend was a huge weekend for Depew Athletics!

Friday, our Girls Modified Basketball team tied their game in last second of regulation then won in overtime 25-19!

The Boys Varsity Basketball team beat Iroquois who was previously unbeaten in ECIC Division III league play 55-51! The boys were led by Christian Pagano's five 3-pointers and team leading 18 points.

At Saturday's ECIC Wrestling Championships, Carson Alberti, who already has over 100 career wins, won the 120 lb. title! Congrats Carson!!!

Six different goal scorers led the Depew Ice Hockey team as they defeated Frontier 6-0 Monday morning at the Harbor Center pushing their record to 6-1-1 in our inaugural Federation Hockey season. Trent Kubiak recorded the shutout for the Wildcats.

post_text:
The Wildcats Boys Hockey team won again on Sunday beating Kenmore East 8-3 extending their record to 4-1-0-1.

Riley Kubiak scored 3 times and got 1 assist to help lead the Wildcats to yet another victory. Dylan Klodzinski continued his hot streak netting 2 goals and adding a helper. Jim Richter and Logan Schwartz added a goal each and Joshua Falter tallied his first goal of the season on a blast from the point. Zach Tominich added 2 assists and so did Aiden Kendall in his first game back with the cats. Nathin Sisti, Aidan Edbauer, and Tyler Connors each had an assist. Trent Kubiak got another win for the Wildcats stopping 16 of 19 shots.

It’s time to show support for your Wildcats Hockey team! Come out Saturday, January 11 to the Northtown Center at 6:25 as they face Amherst. You can see them in action again on Sunday, January 12 in a tough battle against Lewiston-Porter at Buff-State. Face Off time is 1:10 p.m.

The IMPACT Team is holding a Coat Drive January 2-16. We are collecting winter coats and jackets for children and adults (no XL-XXL sizes, please), mittens and gloves, and scarves and hats.

All items must be new or gently-used and clean (no donations exposed to cigarette smoke or pet hair, please).

Donations may be dropped off at Depew High School, M-F from 7:30 a.m.-3 p.m. There is a donation bin in the front foyer.

Items collected will be donated to Journey's End Refugee Services in Buffalo.

For questions, please contact Kim McEwen at 686-5073.

When she's not teaching 8th grade math and algebra, her two children keep her busy with gymnastics and Tae Kwon Do! She loves the Harry Potter movies and Elf. She is also much admired for her handwriting, but she finds typing faster!

post_text:
The Wildcats boys hockey team improved their overall record to 2-1 with a 4-1 victory over Sectional runner-up Kenmore West at Harbor Center on Monday evening!

The Wildcats played strong in the first period but found themselves down 1-0 at the end of the period. In the second period, the cat’s Jim Richter notched his first of the season at 7:08. Tyler Connors added 2 more goals and the Wildcats never looked back, playing sound defensive hockey. Aidan Edbauer added an empty net goal for his second of the season. Trent Kubiak got his first win of the season stopping 19 of 20 shots.

Come out to see your Wildcats in action against #3 ranked West Seneca West, Sunday, December 15 at 1:10 p.m. at the Buffalo State Ice Rink. Admission is $1 for students and $4 for adults.
